#compdef wasi-kit
# ============================================================================
# wasi-kit - Compile native C/C++ projects to WebAssembly via WASI SDK
#             (Node, ?)
#
# Author : Corwin Amber (corwin-of-amber)
# Upstream: https://github.com/corwin-of-amber/wasi-kernel
# npm    : wasi-kernel (binary: wasi-kit)
#
# `wasi-kit` is a thin wrapper around the WASI-SDK toolchain
# (clang / clang++ / llvm-ar) that lets you compile a native
# C/C++ project to WebAssembly without re-engineering the
# project's Makefiles. The trick: drop into the project's
# build, symlink wasi-kit as `gcc`/`g++`/`clang`/`clang++`/`ar`,
# then run `make` normally. Each invocation of the symlinked
# tool dispatches on the basename of argv[0] - so the native
# build still runs unchanged, and wasi-kit additionally emits
# matching .wo (object) / .wa (archive) artifacts compiled
# against the WASI SDK in parallel.
#
# Usage (via symlinked tool names):
#   gcc / g++ / clang / clang++   - compile both native + WASI
#   ar                             - native + WASI archive
#   mv / ln / cp                   - file-op phase
#   wasi-kit / kit.js              - "hijack" phase - the
#                                    bootstrap mode that
#                                    symlinks the wrappers
#                                    into the build dir
#
# Configuration: nearest parent `wasi-kit.json` file -
# per-output-file overrides for {type, fn, native}.
#
# Environment:
#   WASI_SDK           - path to WASI SDK install
#                        (default /opt/wasi-sdk)
#   WASI_KIT           - comma-separated kit flags
#                        ("verbose" prints exec lines)
#
# The @wasmer/wasi lane is built on `@wasmer/wasi ^0.12.0`
# + `@wasmer/wasm-transformer ^0.12.0` + `@wasmer/wasmfs
# ^0.12.0` (declared verbatim at upstream package.json HEAD),
# the canonical Node WASI runtime by Wasmer Inc.
# (github.com/wasmerio/wasmer-js, 800+ stars across the
# wasmer-js packages). @wasmer/wasi implements the WASI
# Preview 1 host interface in pure JavaScript, allowing any
# WASI-compiled Wasm module to run in Node or a browser
# without a native runtime. wasi-kit uses it to verify that
# the WASI-compiled outputs actually execute - the build
# pipeline produces .wo + .wa artifacts and then can
# instantiate them against the JS-WASI host to validate
# behavior without needing a separate runtime install.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 232 :: WebAssembly runtime + WASI host (Wasm spec + WASI Preview)
# Round 1396 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 232 (225th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : bytecodealliance/wasmtime    [R1394 _lunatic]
#   Go      : tetratelabs/wazero           [R1395 _grpc-federation-generator]
#   TS/Node : wasmerio/wasmer-js (@wasmer/wasi)  [R1396 THIS FILE]
#
# @wasmer/wasi rounds out Axis 232 with the *browser-and-
# Node-runnable* slot. wasmtime (Rust) and wazero (Go) are
# both server-side runtimes; @wasmer/wasi is the JS slot
# that runs the same Wasm modules in either Node OR the
# browser. The Bytecode Alliance has its own JS-side
# offering (jco for the component model) but Wasmer's
# WASI-Preview-1 implementation predates jco and remains
# the de-facto choice for "run an existing WASI module in
# Node/browser" use cases.
#
# The three lanes together cover the full Wasm-runtime
# matrix: server-side Rust (wasmtime), server-side Go
# (wazero), and JavaScript host (wasmer-js + jco). Every
# major Wasm deployment target has a canonical runtime in
# the language idiomatic to that target. The cross-runtime
# interop is total at the Wasm spec level - the same
# `.wasm` binary executes identically under any of the
# three. What diverges is the host integration story:
#   - Rust slot (lunatic via wasmtime): Erlang-style actor
#     scheduler wrapping wasmtime instances
#   - Go slot (grpc-federation-generator via wazero): embed
#     wazero in a codegen tool for runtime CEL extensions
#   - Node slot (wasi-kit via @wasmer/wasi): use JS-WASI to
#     validate WASI-compiled output during a build pipeline
#
# Three host-language-idiomatic embedding patterns for the
# same canonical Wasm spec.
# ============================================================================

_wasi-kit() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '*: :_files'
}

_wasi-kit "$@"
